<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="545" pageId="14" pageNumber="543" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,403,1978]" box="[199,345,1303,1329]" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1303,1329]" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">Description.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,403,1978]" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">
Carapace length female 315–327 µm, height 147–152 µm, height/length = 0.45–0.48 (n=2), male 305–310 µm, height 125–129 µm, height/length = 0.41–0.42 (n=2). Lateral view roughly semicircular, with strongly arched dorsal margin and slightly concave ventral margin, anterior and posterior margins similar in size, with maximum curvature towards ventral margins (
<figureCitation box="[545,727,1447,1474]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 6. A–D, Cobanocythere sp. A, LV, ext. B, RV, int. C, Cp, vent., anterior to right. D, Cp, dor., anterior to left. E–J, Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. (female, LBM 1430009564). E, LV, ext. F, RV, ext. G, LV, ext., detail of postero-ventral margin. H, RV, ext., detail of postero-ventral margin. I, LV, int. J, RV, int. Scale bar = 100 µm for A, B, E, F, 126 µm for G–J, and 23 µm for C &amp; D. White triangles indicate the two semicircular depressions on the valves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626921/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">Figs 6E, F, I &amp; J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[737,825,1447,1474]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">7A &amp; B</figureCitation>
). Internal view of both valves with wide calcified inner lamellae. Postero-ventral inner margin of inner calcified inner lamella straight to slightly sinuous, and with three shallow grooves running sub-parallel to each other and outer margin. Line of concrescence strongly deviating from outer margin along posterior and anterior margins, in places forming inner margin. Very edge of postero-ventral corner with two small, semi-circular depressions (
<figureCitation box="[707,821,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 6. A–D, Cobanocythere sp. A, LV, ext. B, RV, int. C, Cp, vent., anterior to right. D, Cp, dor., anterior to left. E–J, Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. (female, LBM 1430009564). E, LV, ext. F, RV, ext. G, LV, ext., detail of postero-ventral margin. H, RV, ext., detail of postero-ventral margin. I, LV, int. J, RV, int. Scale bar = 100 µm for A, B, E, F, 126 µm for G–J, and 23 µm for C &amp; D. White triangles indicate the two semicircular depressions on the valves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626921/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">Fig. 6H–J</figureCitation>
; marked with white triangles on 
<figureCitation box="[1184,1333,1591,1618]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 6. A–D, Cobanocythere sp. A, LV, ext. B, RV, int. C, Cp, vent., anterior to right. D, Cp, dor., anterior to left. E–J, Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. (female, LBM 1430009564). E, LV, ext. F, RV, ext. G, LV, ext., detail of postero-ventral margin. H, RV, ext., detail of postero-ventral margin. I, LV, int. J, RV, int. Scale bar = 100 µm for A, B, E, F, 126 µm for G–J, and 23 µm for C &amp; D. White triangles indicate the two semicircular depressions on the valves." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626921/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">Fig. 6G and I</figureCitation>
). Adductor muscle scars with row of four closely spaced scars, and one large frontal scar. Dorsal view laterally compressed with bulge in middle area. Surface of valves with smooth surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,403,1978]" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">
Antennule with five segments (
<figureCitation box="[558,648,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
). First and second segments elongate. Third segment short, with one short apical-dorsal seta. Fourth segment elongate with one short dorsal seta at mid-length position and one short apical-dorsal seta. Fifth segment elongate, apically with one short seta, and two aesthetasc-like setae fused together at base, one with widened bulbous end, and one thinner with rounded end.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,403,1978]" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">
Antenna basis elongate, supporting three-segmented endopod and long, jointed exopod (
<figureCitation box="[1179,1268,1843,1870]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="543">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
). First endopodal segment with one short apical-ventral seta. Second endopodal segment with one seta on ventral margin, near mid-length, and one apical-ventral seta. Third endopodal segment small, with two short, curved claws. Exopodite reaching to end of claws of endopodite.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="544" startId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" targetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1823,1992]" pageId="15" pageNumber="544">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,1823,1848]" pageId="15" pageNumber="544">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" box="[291,624,1824,1848]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="15" pageNumber="544" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[291,624,1824,1848]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="544">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[635,720,1824,1848]" pageId="15" pageNumber="544">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[635,720,1824,1848]" pageId="15" pageNumber="544" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Mandible palp four-segmented, but division between second and third segments weakly defined (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1366,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7E</figureCitation>
). First segment with one short seta on apical inner edge. Second segment elongate with two setae on inner apical corner, and one sub-apical seta on outer edge. Third segment elongate with one stout, long and one much smaller sub-apical setae on inner edge, and one stout, long apical seta. Terminal segment elongate with two medium-length apical claw-like setae. Coxa small with about five teeth and thin, relatively long seta on outer edge (
<figureCitation box="[1197,1282,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Maxillula palp with very indistinct segmentation between first and second segments (
<figureCitation box="[1171,1262,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7G</figureCitation>
). First segment with one stout apical seta on outer edge. Second segment with two long, curved apical setae. First, second and third endites with about four, three and four apical setae respectively.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Fifth limb first segment with one apical seta (
<figureCitation box="[704,794,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7H</figureCitation>
). Second segment very elongate, with small antero-apical seta. Third and fourth segments approximately equal in length, with fourth segment supporting small, curved claw.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Brushed-shaped organs of male consisting of small elongate base supporting numerous, fine setae (not figured).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Sixth limb first and second segments thin and very elongate, each with antero-apical seta (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1299,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7I</figureCitation>
). Third segment shortest of limb, with no setae. Fourth segment longer than third, and supporting small, curved claw, slightly smaller than on fifth limb.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Seventh limb large and robust (
<figureCitation box="[556,638,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7J</figureCitation>
). First segment with wide base tapering distally. Second segment supporting thick seta tapering to thin distal part. Third segment slightly longer than fourth, both much shorter than second segment (about 40% of length), fourth segment with large, robust, curved claw.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Male sexual organs symmetrical, basal capsule quadrate, inner and outer margins sub-parallel, distal lobe very lightly sclerotized, large and triangular, terminating with tightly rounded tip (
<figureCitation box="[1036,1128,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7K</figureCitation>
). Upper ramus elongate irregular oval. Clasping apparatus with straight inner edge and bulbous outer edge. Copulatory duct hooked-shaped, distally slender and straight.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
Posterior of female with large, angular genital lobe, caudal ramus consisting of small base and two flexible claws, and large, rounded caudal process fringed with long setules (tending to clump together in dissection slides) (
<figureCitation box="[160,247,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[153,1435,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. A, RV, ext., male (LBM 1430009563). B, RV, ext., female (LBM 1430009565). C, antennule (LBM 1430009561). D, antenna (LBM 1430009561). E, mandibular palp (LBM 1430009566). F, mandibular coxa (LBM 1430009561). G, maxillula (branchial plate not drawn) (LBM 1430009566). H, fifth limb (LBM 1430009566). I, sixth limb (LBM 1430009566). J, seventh limb (LBM 1430009561). K, hemipenis (LBM 1430009561). L, posterior of body, female (LBMM 1430009562)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626923/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 7L</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="545" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1051,1077]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Remarks.</emphasis>
Of the 12 other species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann" authorityYear="1954" box="[736,932,1051,1077]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[736,932,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Microloxoconcha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, all differ from 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[209,298,1087,1113]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[209,298,1087,1113]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the shape of the hemipenes, with the closest being 
<taxonomicName authority="Higashi et al., 2011" authorityName="Higashi" authorityYear="2011" box="[894,1432,1087,1113]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimorpha">
<emphasis box="[894,1206,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Microloxoconcha dimorpha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Higashi, R. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A. &amp; Kimura, H. &amp; Kato, K." box="[1212,1432,1087,1113]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" pagination="142 - 152" refId="ref13153" refString="Higashi, R., Tsukagoshi, A., Kimura, H. &amp; Kato, K. (2011) Male dimorphism in a new interstitial species of the genus Microloxoconcha (Podocopida: Ostracoda). Journal of Crustacean Biology, 31 (1), 142 - 152. https: // doi. org / 10.1651 / 09 - 3234.1" type="journal article" year="2011">
Higashi 
<emphasis box="[1306,1361,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">et al.</emphasis>
, 2011
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from 
<collectingRegion box="[211,315,1123,1149]" country="Japan" name="Shizuoka" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Shizuoka</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[368,486,1123,1149]" country="Japan" name="Kanagawa" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Kanagawa</collectingRegion>
Prefectures. However, the hemipenes of 
<taxonomicName box="[939,1085,1123,1149]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimorpha">
<emphasis box="[939,1085,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">M. dimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are asymmetrical, and the carapace, although also elongate, is noticeably different in shape; in lateral view the apex of the curvature of the anterior and posterior margins are shallower and positioned higher than those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" box="[968,1331,1195,1221]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[968,1331,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1339,1429,1195,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1339,1429,1195,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, which has a noticeable angle at the postero-ventral corner. The chaetotaxy of the appendages of 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[317,406,1267,1293]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[317,406,1267,1293]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Higashi &amp; Tsukagoshi, 2008" authorityName="Higashi &amp; Tsukagoshi" authorityYear="2008" box="[611,1301,1267,1293]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kikaijimaensis">
<emphasis box="[611,973,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Microloxoconcha kikaijimaensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Higashi, R. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A." box="[980,1301,1267,1293]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" pagination="157 - 173" refId="ref13098" refString="Higashi, R. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A. (2008) Two new species of Microloxoconcha (Crustacea: Ostracoda: Podocopida) from Japan, with a redescription of the genus. Species Diversity, 13, 157 - 173. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / specdiv. 13.157" type="journal article" year="2008">Higashi &amp; Tsukagoshi, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which is so far only known from Kikaijima Island, 
<collectingRegion box="[598,851,1303,1329]" country="Japan" name="Kagoshima" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Kagoshima Prefecture</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[863,930,1303,1329]" name="Japan" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Japan</collectingCountry>
, about 
<quantity box="[1012,1098,1302,1329]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" unit="km" value="650.0">650 km</quantity>
south of Tsushima. Both species have a large, robust seta on the second segment of the seventh limb, two robust and one tiny setae on the third segment of the mandible, and similar caudal rami and large caudal processes in the females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="545" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,501,1410,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
This species was recovered from a shallow hole dug into the bed of a tidal part of a small river, with a salinity of 0.3% at time of collecting (low tide), and about 
<quantity box="[1051,1123,1446,1473]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="16" pageNumber="545" unit="m" value="150.0">150 m</quantity>
from the sea. The substrate consisted mostly of flattened pebbles of sedimentary rock with a little fine sand and mud (
<figureCitation box="[1160,1281,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,418,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-99@2.[151,1435,417,1860]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Type localities of Vestalenula gravata sp. nov. (A &amp; B) and Microloxoconcha semicircularis sp. nov. (C–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6626910" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6626910/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="545">Fig. 2C–E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
